external_knowledge:
- "highest rated resources" refers to resources with the highest average ratings; 
- "published after 2020" means the resources' published dates are after '2020-01-01'; 
- "excluding any without ratings" implies that only resources with at least one rating are considered.

; The query assumes that a higher rating indicates a better quality or more popular resource; 
; The number of hits can be considered a measure of how often a resource is accessed or viewed, which can be an indicator of its popularity or relevance; 
; The average user rating provides a metric to gauge the overall user satisfaction or perception of a resource; 
; The count of reviews and unique reviewers can be seen as indicators of user engagement with the resource; 
; The collection count shows how many different collections a resource is part of, which may reflect its versatility or relevance across different contexts.

sql:
SELECT resource_type, COUNT(*) AS type_count
FROM resources
GROUP BY resource_type;

SELECT resource_id, AVG(rating) AS average_rating, COUNT(rating_id) AS total_ratings
FROM resource_ratings
GROUP BY resource_id;

